BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 738.00 Tm (Inversion of Control is the principle; the IoC container - also called the application context - is the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 723.00 Tm (part of Spring that implements it. Instead of your code controlling when and how objects are) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 708.00 Tm (created, you hand that responsibility to the container. At startup it scans for your annotated) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 693.00 Tm (components, creates one instance of each - a singleton by default - works out what each one) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 678.00 Tm (depends on, and injects those dependencies automatically. Look at the diagram: the container) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 663.00 Tm (holds the controller, the service, and the repository beans. In our app it creates the) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 648.00 Tm (GreetingService once, sees that HelloController needs a GreetingService, and hands the same) Tj ET
