BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 487.00 Tm (Spring can inject a dependency in three places, and the trade-offs are worth knowing. Constructor) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 472.00 Tm (injection, on the left, is the modern best practice: the dependency is passed into the constructor) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 457.00 Tm (and stored in a final field. It can never be null and never change after construction, the class is) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 442.00 Tm (easy to instantiate in tests, and required dependencies are obvious. With a single constructor,) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 427.00 Tm (at-Autowired is even optional. Field injection, on the right, is the shortest - Spring sets the field) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 412.00 Tm (directly. We use it in today's lab purely for clarity, but it's harder to test and hides required) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 397.00 Tm (dependencies. And setter injection - Spring calls a setter - is best for optional dependencies that) Tj ET
BT /F1 11.00 Tf 0.120 0.120 0.140 rg 1 0 0 1 72.00 382.00 Tm (can change after the object is built.) Tj ET
